[
    {
        "content": "<p>A while ago some asked about the <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Chern-Weil.20Theory\">Chern classes</a>. Right now it seems like there are many lemmas about manifolds with boundary that might best be understood as falling under the theory of Thom spaces.</p>\n<p>One of those sources is the thread about model spaces, in which a key lemma concerns invariance of domain. Invariance of domain follows from Spanier-Whitehead duality concerning the Thom space of a stable normal bundle of a manifold.</p>\n<p>In the case of a sphere immersed in a sphere this subsumes invariance of domain implying that ‚Ñù‚Åø and ‚Ñù·µê are not homeomorphic for n and m distinct.</p>\n<p>A complete point of view for that theory seems just as important as the eventual completion of the thread concerning Chern classes, while giving organizing principles for the boundaries of smooth manifolds.</p>\n<p>I thought it could be a good idea to discuss that in a theead of its own. Maybe we can collect progress here- even though it is far off, even the basic result of the inverse function theorem requires invariance of domain in the proof of openness. This result has its natural place in Alexander and Spanier-Whitehead duality, in which complements of submanifolds are related to the Thom space of a normal bundle.</p>",
        "id": 524109952,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1749970501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Let me keep it short: I think Thom spaces would be great to have eventually --- but adding these to mathlib feels like a longer-term project. (For instance, mathlib doesn't have smooth submanifolds yet; I'm working on these. Then you want to define sub-bundles in general, and the normal bundle in particular. Then you begin to talk about the stable normal bundle of a manifold, etc.)</p>",
        "id": 524111029,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1749972167
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Two days ago, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"111080\">@Floris van Doorn</span> mentioned that you could presumably also define singular homology via Eilenberg-MacLane spaces (in a manner similar to homotopy type theory): while EM spaces are certainly nice to have, I don't think they provide a short-term faster route to invariance of domain.</p>",
        "id": 524111123,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1749972267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for helping me with what's current. I think I'm not ready to prove the axioms yet- maybe in several months. </p>\n<p>Just now I found the slides at your website and I'm reading through them.</p>",
        "id": 524111960,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1749973390
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On the other hand I think that the homotopy equivalence between S‚Å∞ and S‚Åø‚Å∫¬π minus the C¬π-submanifold of S‚Åø (however immersed) is more useful than meets the eye: both invariance of domain for C¬π-functions and the inverse function theorem use<br>\nit. (edit: or probably better to say, they follow from it, since the existence of a tubular neighborhood is demonstrated using the inverse function theorem and not the other way around).</p>",
        "id": 524112580,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1749974137
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm sure that homotopy equivalence can be used somewhere.<br>\nI'm not sure this would be used in mathlib to prove these results, though: I'd rather have invariance of domain for C‚Å∞ functions (using homology of spheres, which follows from the homology axioms) and prove the inverse function theorem on manifolds by reduction to the normed space case.</p>",
        "id": 524149962,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750014422
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In fact, I have \"most\" of the second point on an old branch --- which needs some dusting off, polishing and completing it. (Help with that could be welcome.)</p>",
        "id": 524149990,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750014458
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"928979\">Jeremy Ravenel</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/The.20Thom.20isomorphism.20for.20a.20normal.20bundle/near/524111960\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks for helping me with what's current. I think I'm not ready to prove the axioms yet- maybe in several months. </p>\n<p>Just now I found the slides at your website and I'm reading through them.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Sure, no worries. If you feel like trying a project, feel free to DM me and we can think about a suitable one.</p>",
        "id": 524150100,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750014594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(There are certainly lots of other things, with a lower barrier to entry, that would be useful to have.)</p>",
        "id": 524150113,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750014609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>4.4 <a href=\"https://www.uvm.edu/~smillere/TProjects/ADu20s.pdf\">here</a> is pretty close to the axioms.</p>\n<p>Maybe like uou suggested in the spirit of Mathlib to finish the openness part of the inverse function theorem by assuming invariance of domain because of how the homology axioms and Mayer-Vietoris axiom are not done yet and because it is stronger than necessary.</p>",
        "id": 524174193,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750045223
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However I can't follow why the homology of a limit works in that case, and the proof of theorem 9.24 in Rudin's Principles of Mathematical Analysis is also very interesting:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/vQ-7odacl2uRbpuOQQc8QBhu/image.jpeg\">image.jpeg</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/vQ-7odacl2uRbpuOQQc8QBhu/image.jpeg\" title=\"image.jpeg\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/jpeg\" data-original-dimensions=\"2874x1686\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/vQ-7odacl2uRbpuOQQc8QBhu/image.jpeg/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 524181152,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750051656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>After some thought I realized it is just that œÄ‚ÇÄ is left adjoint that one needs for the connected components, along with the MV-sequence in 4.3 at the link. I think that is enough for invariance of domain.</p>",
        "id": 524186906,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750055719
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/476772/reference-for-homotopy-groups-of-filtered-homotopy-colimits\">Evidently this also works for œÄõ≤î of filtered colimits.</a></p>",
        "id": 524206116,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750063221
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for your help with this problem <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"634338\">@Michael Rothgang</span>  . Could you direct me to the progress you've made?</p>",
        "id": 524206352,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750063309
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If a topological space P is a disjoint union of subspaces X and Y as a set, and X with the subspace topology is homeomorphic to a space with a single connected component, and Y with the subspace topology is homeomorphic to a space with a single connected component, and P has two connected components, then both X and Y must be both closed and open in P.</p>",
        "id": 524217111,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750067069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"928979\">Jeremy Ravenel</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/The.20Thom.20isomorphism.20for.20a.20normal.20bundle/near/524206352\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks for your help with this problem <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"634338\">Michael Rothgang</span>  . Could you direct me to the progress you've made?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Do you mean for the inverse function theorem? (I didn't work on Mayer-Vietoris.)</p>",
        "id": 524218537,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750067568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"634338\">@Michael Rothgang</span> Yes that- this week I have time to study it and maybe I can make some progress.</p>\n<p>(The Mayer-Vietoris sequence follows from the ES-axioms)</p>",
        "id": 524220445,
        "sender_full_name": "Jeremy Ravenel",
        "timestamp": 1750068162
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sure! I just dug up my old branch and adapted it to current master. I'll push it soon. (edit: <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/26115\">#26115</a>)</p>",
        "id": 524745701,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750264606
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Be warned, though: the proofs are in an intermediate state of \"being broken\" --- just looking at them may not be the clearest. (Feel free to ask me, though --- and perhaps I can take some time tomorrow to polish this slightly).</p>",
        "id": 524746075,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1750264754
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"928979\">Jeremy Ravenel</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/The.20Thom.20isomorphism.20for.20a.20normal.20bundle/near/524206116\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/476772/reference-for-homotopy-groups-of-filtered-homotopy-colimits\">Evidently this also works for œÄõ≤î of filtered colimits.</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This reference seems to be quite wrong. If \"Space\" means \"simplicial set\", then it is ok. If \"Space\" means \"topological space\", it might be wrong. In the category of topological spaces, if <code>T</code> is compact, it is unclear to me that <code>Hom(T, -)</code> commutes with filtered colimits. What I know is that if <code>X ‚ü∂ Y</code> is a transfinite composition of closed <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> inclusions, then <code>Hom(T, Y)</code> identifies to a suitable colimit of <code>Hom</code> types (I have formalized this at <a href=\"https://github.com/joelriou/topcat-model-category/blob/e5705bfcc6944a0f8119f7b1cf717b686f39fbfd/TopCatModelCategory/TopCat/T1Inclusion.lean#L310\">https://github.com/joelriou/topcat-model-category/blob/e5705bfcc6944a0f8119f7b1cf717b686f39fbfd/TopCatModelCategory/TopCat/T1Inclusion.lean#L310</a> ; <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110032\">@Reid Barton</span> also did; more details in the book by Hovey, <em>Model categories</em>, paragraph 2.4). For a general direct system of topological spaces, I would not claim it is true. (The technical details about such issues are omitted in many references.)</p>",
        "id": 524767876,
        "sender_full_name": "Jo√´l Riou",
        "timestamp": 1750273685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>thanks for the correction, I agree. However in our case these are inclusions of open subobjects and so this should in fact follow from compactness of spheres and discs. I found a reference of Proposition 2B.1. in Hatcher for that. (sorry, I've realized I just responded from a friend's account - Jeremy)</p>",
        "id": 524804860,
        "sender_full_name": "pro-Lie stabilizer",
        "timestamp": 1750298050
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"459699\">@Jo√´l Riou</span>, the reference given is fully in infinity-category land and so \"Space\" means \"the quasicagegory of Kan complexes\".</p>\n<p>It's still a bit early for using infinity-categorical references for formalisation in mathlib, though</p>",
        "id": 524839291,
